Files:
- scripts/dev.ts (replace execFileSync call with execSync string command)

Context:
Node.js 24 introduced DEP0190: 'Passing args to a child process with shell option true can lead to security vulnerabilities, as the arguments are not escaped, only concatenated.' This fires when spawn/execFileSync is called with both an args array AND shell:true. The dev.ts file runs lefthook install at startup to keep git hooks up-to-date after lefthook version bumps.

Current code (scripts/dev.ts, lines 383-390):
```
const { execFileSync } = await import('node:child_process');
try {
  execFileSync('npx', ['lefthook', 'install'], { cwd: ROOT, stdio: 'ignore', shell: true });
} catch {
  // Non-fatal — lefthook may not be installed yet (first clone before npm install)
}
```

Changes:
Replace execFileSync with execSync using a single string command (no args array, so no DEP0190):
```
const { execSync } = await import('node:child_process');
try {
  execSync('npx lefthook install', { cwd: ROOT, stdio: 'ignore' });
} catch {
  // Non-fatal — lefthook may not be installed yet (first clone before npm install)
}
```
This is safe on all platforms: on Windows, npx resolves .cmd shims via PATH regardless of shell:true; execSync with a string command uses sh on Unix, cmd.exe on Windows — both resolve npx correctly.

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the surrounding block structure (the IIFE-style block with braces, lines 383-390)
- Do NOT change any other spawn/exec calls in the file
- The catch block must remain as-is (non-fatal fallback)
